{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_jasmine_ver01/data/sn78000533/00340580345/1945110801/0337.xml":{"full_text":"7\nn\nOFFICIAL ORGAN\nNATIONAL BROTHERHOOD OF\n^OPERATIVE POTTERS V\nVOL. XLIX, NO. 28\nHe also vigorously attacked two con\ngressional committees for holding up\naction for months on the full employ\nment bill and proposals to increase\nunemployment compensation pay\nments, and call on Congress to reverse\nits decision to kill the U. S. Employ\nment Service.\nTruman\u2019s wage raising recommen\ndations were implemented with an\namendment to Executive Order 9599,\nissued Aug. 18, which had permitted\nwage increases where they would not\nbe used as the basis for yking hif^her\nprices for products.\nWage Boosts Possible\nWithout Price Rise,\n0^ \"V \u25a0M*-. A!1\n-.*.-<p></p>Declares\nPresident\nSCORNS COMMITTEE FOR HOLDING\nUP ACTION ON EMPLOYMENT BILL\nv THAT IS SO IMPORTANT TO WORKERS\nWashington (FP).\u2014Warning against the disastrous effects\nof a $20 billion pay cut facing American workers, President Tru\nman Oct. 30 called on industry, in a radio address, to increase wage\nrates to compensate for $he guj, ip take-home pay now that war pro\nduction is over. .1 I? \"3\nThe President offered no formula and suggested no percentage\nof increase but gave five reasons why, he said, American industry\ncan well afford to grant substantial increases and thus avoid the\ndangers of deflation, unemployment and relief.\nIndustry\u2019s proposal for price increases to make up for wage\nincreases \u201ccannot be accepted under*-------------------------------------------------\nany circumstances,\u201d Truman declared.\n\u201cTo accept it would mean but one\nthing\u2014inflation. An increase in\nwages, if it were accompanied by an\nincrease in the cost of living, would\nnot help even the workers themselves.\nEvery extra dollar that would be put\nin their pay envelopes under these\ncircumstances would be needed to\nmeet the higher living expenses re\nsulting from increased prices.\u201d i\nAt the same time Truman told labor\nthat \u201cwe cannot hope, with a reduced\nwork-week, to maintain now the same\ntake-home pay for labor generally\nthat it has had during the war. There\nwill have to be a drop. But the na\ntion cannot afford to have the drop\ntoo drastic.\u201d\nThe amendment, known as Execu\n(Tvm to Pago Six)\nBuffalo Scribe\nSeeks Data On\nHealth Program\nthe\nthe\nfor\nBuffalo, N. J.\u2014Employees of\nBuffalo pottery who are taking\naluminum therapy treatments\nsilicosis are loud in their praise of the\nwonderful results obtained. We men\ntion this fact for the benefit \u00bbf those\nthroughout the trade who seem to be\na little skeptical of the benefits de\nrived from these treatments.\nWhile the program for the elimina\ntion of dust hazards throughout the\nshop has not gone forward as fast as\ndesired, our dust counts are low ex\ncept in a few spots and these will be\ntaken care of when the equipment is\navailable.\nThe main aisles of the clayshop are\nswept and then gone over with an\nelectric scrubber every day, but we\nstill have many cases of poor house\nkeeping, due mostly to new employees\ndropping ware on the floor and ne\nglecting to pick it up. The foremen\u2019s\nattention should be called to such\npractice.\nWe note with sympathy the efforts\nof Local Union. 99 to interest their\nfirm in obtaining the necessary equip\nment to administer treatments for sili\ncosis. We feel sure that if they would\ngive it the proper investigation, they\nwould not wait until an employee ac\nquired siliqosis before making the\ntreatments available for them.\nAluminum is a preventive and not a\ncure for silicosis, and we believe many\n(Turn to Page Six)\nGreen Calls Far Thirty-Hour Week\nAs Economic \"Must\u201d To Speed Jobs\nfy. Chicago\u2014Proposals by big business\nto lengthen the basic work week to\n45-hours instead of granting increases\nin wage rates were summarily reject\ned here by AFL President William\nGreen.\nInstead, Mr. Green emphasized it\nwould soon become an \u201ceconomic ne\ncessity\u201d to place workers throughout\nthe country on a six-hour and thirty\nhour week.\nSpeajcing before the convention of\nthe Building Service Employes Inter\nnational Union, Mr. Green said the\nwork day must be reduced to spread\nemployment \u201cor we will be faced with\na serious unemployment problem.\u201d\nScientific and technological im\nprovements in industry made it pos\nsible for \u201cless and less workers to pro\nduce more and more goods,\u201d the AFL\npresident added, and the reduced work\nweek was the \u201conly practical method\u201d\nto distribute work.\nHa pledged that the AFL would\nenter the labor-management confer\nence in Washington with every de-\nKir4-'\n\u2022*3\nS\u2019.. ta.\nSpokesmen Take\nDiverse Paths\nAt Conference\ni\nWashington (FP). The approach\nof American management to the\nna\u00ad,\ntional labor-management conference\nwhich opened Nov. 5 was character\u00ad'\nized by some of the differences that\nmade labor's split both apparent and\nreal. \u2019L '3\nPresident Eric Johnston of the U.\nS. Chamber of Commerce, smiling into\nmovie cameras in a manner that would\nplease most Hollywood directors, was\nconciliation and mediation itself. He\nwas the typical chamber of commerce\nspokesman and he called for an end to\n\u201cthunderous statements and wild\nepithets,\u201d and suggested that labor\nand management, in the future \u201cmeet\nless often in the headlines and more'\noften around the council table.\u201d He\ncalled for self-analysis and for self\ncriticism, asked for cool heads and\nwarm hearts.\nOn the other hand, President Ira\nMosher of the National Association of\nManufacturers, pledged that organiza\ntion\u2019s cooperation to the conference\nbut insisted that his organization \u201cwill\nnever compromise the ideal of individ\nual enterprise\u201d and called for public\nacknowledgement of areas of dis\nagreement.\nMosher insisted that these dis\nagreements must \u201cnot be glossed over\nby the utterance of pious platitudes\nand the appearance of a harmony that\ndoes not exist,\u201d and made a spectacu\nlar play on words when he insisted\nthat if disagreements come it will not\nbe because the NAM\u201d came here with\nany lack of a liberal and progressive\nprogram.\nDiffering sharply from Secretary of\nCommerce Wallace, Mosher implied\nthat the issue of wages and prices\nshould not be a subject for conference\nconsideration. He said \u201cthis is not a\nnational collective bargaining confer\nence. Our function is simply to recom\nmend those procedures by which in\ndustrial relations can be conducted,\nmost effectively at the levels where\nthey belong.\u201d\nSENIORITY RIGHTS ARE\nUPHELD IN LAYOFFS\nA long campaign by AFL unions,\nparticularly those representing navy\nyard workers, for recognition by\nUncle Sam of seniority rights has\nfinally brought results.\nThe Civil Service Commission an\nnounced new regulations under which\nseniority\u2014that is, length of service\u2014\nwill be the main factor in determin\ning who shall be laid off first as war\ntime working forces are reduced.\nIn the past, layoffs were governed\nby \u201cefficiency ratings\u201d or only by the\nwhim of officials in charge, but now\nseniority will get prime consideration,\nwith merit ratings secondary. Senior\nity will also be the governing factor\nin determining a worker\u2019s position on\ncivil service reemployment registers.\n''J'\n4ts.\n^1.\nV\nI\nLocal Union 99\nin u\nTo Hold Party\nmagic following the dinner.\n^llOp vommi\nto\ntermination to work out a plan\nminimize strikes* Mr. Green said that\nhis organization would make a sincere\neffort to bring about true collective\nbargaining.\nMr. Green told the 500 delegates\nthat he would lend his support to an\norganization drive to bring into the\nbuilding service union, headed by Wil\nliam F. McFetridge of Chicago, jani\ntors, maids, bowling alley employes\nand* others. He said those to be or\nganized reached potential millions in\nnumber.\nThe1 AFL would do anything pos\nsible to let the union bars down for\nservicemen, Mr. Green assured the\nunion delegates. He said that most\nunions had voted to allow veterans\nknowing various trades to enter\nunions without payment of high en\ntrance fees.\nThe AFL president praised produc\ntion by union men during the war and\nsaid that no single serviceman went\nwithout anything he needed during\nthe action in the European and Pa\ncific theaters.\nFined By U\u00bb lx*l\n5 WL \"S' at\" 5-^rvr \"\u2022ii s 4 U, v 4 i 1\u00ab. r*jj ^,Js4\nRecord Crowd I\nAt Limoges\nJordah And Turner I\nAmong Those Present\nSu^ by\nhcommittee- k\n$1.75 each which we think is a bar-1\nBetween the decal girls and filler-1^\nKnowles, it looks as though the Stand-\ning Committee is in for a busy ses-\nsion. Good luck to them and we hope\nn/'iVT*fYTvr A IVf A\nTOBACCO PRODUCTS I\nStrike Pall Mall or Melachrino cig-1\narets. The latter are on the forbidden\nCleopatra,\ncigars.\nxAXi-.\u2019jX\nIje ratter# era I a\nEAST LIVERPOOL, OHIO, THURSDAY, NOVEMBER 8, 1945\nah.\n\u2022Snook' Partv 5fe Sp^\nbpook Fmy Wage Topic At Wheeling\n1 11 r.K.r.H.pre.nuj\nWashington (FP).\u2014Organized lab-1\nof Sebring was rewarded for having I \u201cSurely all of us must be fully I Note1 labor .leaders from the lower\nP0*\n1____ u v I.. \"IU wie\nMills, secretary Hugh Dailey. Mike y.m.\nthe most original costume, while the I conscious of the complexities of the|part .of the 8tate who are *n att\u00aend- IwWfff I Wff\ni Misses Marie Crewson and Jane Ber-1 problems which we will be called upon Iance include C. J. Sattler, Commission\nger received a prize for being thelto solve even if the work pf the con-ler Lai\u00b0r\u00bb Thomas Cairns, president Io^o\nmost comic \u201ccouple.\u201d Iference is confined exclusively to the|\u00aef State Federation and secretary\nRoy and Vivan Shrimplin, popular considerations of each of the 7 points (treasurer, V