s that will keep the economic\nwheels turning Full employment in\neverything that the words imply. Ex\ncess profits should go into wages and\nthose industries where it is proven\nthey cannot meet the best standard 'in\nthe payment of wages should be per\nmitted to increase prices.\nThis in conjunction with the pro\ntective tariff like this country never\nhad before, one that will be fool\nproof and insure that no workman\nwill walk the streets because of the\nlarge volume of foreign products be\ning sold in our markets. It is time\nthe American people call a halt to\nour representatives permitting condi\ntions mentioned to exist.\nIn acknowledging the request of the\n0. C. of Local No. 6, sometime ago I\nstated through these columns that\nmany of our members were expressing\nthemselves as impatient with the red\ntape and slowness in action of the\nWar Labor Board on our pending\npropositions. However, since that time\nthe relaxing of the stringent price and\n(Turn to Page Two)\nSpaulding Chind\nTo Hold Party On\nThursday, Nov. 15\nSebring, Ohio.\u2014Thursday, Novem\nber 15 has been the date set for the\nthird annual dinner for employees of\nthe Spaulding China Company, the\ncommittee on arrangements announced\nthis week.\nThe affair as in former years will\nbe held in the decorating department\nof the plant which has been decorated\nfor the occasion and will be under the\nsupervision of the social committee. 7\nRoast turkey with all the \u2018trim\nmings\u2019 comprises the menu and will\nbe served by a committee headed by'\nMrs. Erma Syme as chairman and\nassisted by Mrs. Myrtle French and\nMrs. Leeanna Smith. Albo Green is\nchairman of the refreshment commit-4\ntee.\nAn invitation has been extended to/\nmembers of the Executive Board to\nbe with us on this gala occasion and^ y\nwe sincerely hope official duties will*\nnot hinder their acceptance. 4\nFrom all indications this year\u2019s\u2019^\nparty will surpass any of previous/^\nyears and the employees of the Spaul- 4\nding China Company, affiliated with,/\nLocal Union 178-, N. B. of O. P., wishi.\nto take this means of expressing our\nsincere thanks to Br. George Stanford,\u2022\ngeneral manager, whose generosity\nmakes these affairs possible. Each\nyear the firm contributes a generous/\namount to the social committee to de-'\nfray expenses for entertainment for\ntheir employees.\u2014O. C. 174.\nam\nA\n(FirST WOV6 Of U116111DlOyIIIGUT KvOOrTvCI\n0.\u00abA I^k*l****\nBlft wIOwlGiBS IS rF&BlCTQO\nengaged in war Work have already had\ntheir war jobs terminated by cancel\nlation of war contracts,\u201d Clague\nstated. \u201cSome 3 mililon of these ap\nparently moved to peace jobs in the\nsame establishments without any un\nemployment at all. Slightly over 2:\nmillion came to unemployment com\npensation agencies to file claims, but\nonly a little over 1 million of them\nare actually receiving benefits now.\nThe others found jobs quickly, or\nwere disqualified from benefits. About\n1 mililon of these war workers are\nstill unaccounted for. They have\neither retired, or found jobs without\napplying for benefits, or will apply for\nbenefits in the future.\n\u201cFor the first time since the end\nof the war, the total number of un\nemployment compensation claims\nshowed a small decline for the week\nended Oct. 13, the latest for which\nfigures are available. Until then, the.\nclaims increased steadily from week\nto week, reaching a peak of 1.7 mil\nlion fbr the week ended Oct. 6,\n(Tan to Page Three)\nVsfta\n1\nI\nI\n39\n\u25a0jft\n4\u00bb\n.1","height":"26358","width":"20121"}}
